In the complex plane, let the vertices of the triangle be $a = 5,$ $b = 2i \sqrt{3},$ and $c = 0.$  Let $e$ be one of the vertices, where $e$ is real.  A point on the line passing through $a = 5$ and $b = 2i \sqrt{3}$ can be expressed in the form
\[f = (1 - t) a + tb = 5(1 - t) + 2ti \sqrt{3}.\]We want the third vertex $d$ to lie on the line through $b$ and $c,$ which is the imaginary axis, so its real part is 0.

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E, F;
real e, t;

A = (5,0);
B = (0,2*sqrt(3));
C = (0,0);

e = 1;
t = (e + 5)/11;
E = (e,0);
F = ((1 - t)*5,2*t*sqrt(3));
D = rotate(60,E)*(F);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(D--E--F--cycle);

